If I am using fenced-code-blocks with safe_mode = escape, it will escape also the pre and code tags. 
For example:

```
int main( char** argc ) { 
    std::cout << "hello"; 
}
```

I would expect same result as here on Github, instead I get &lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;int main( char*\* argc ) { std::cout &lt;&lt; "hello"; }&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

``````
    ```python
    class Plugin:
        def __init__(self):
            pass

        def del_(self):
            pass
``````

output is:

```
   class Plugin:
    def __init__(self):
        pass

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">del_</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="k">pass</span>
```

Some kind of conflict with these two involving blank lines and/or new lines.

Example code (two new lines of either type, 4 spaces indent):

``` c
void foo() {

    x = 1;
```

I fixed as:

```
    if "fenced-code-blocks" in self.extras:
        text = self._do_fenced_code_blocks(text)
    else:
        text = self._do_code_blocks(text)
```
